&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from the Police and Crime Commissioner for Cleveland [CST0067][bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The following response has been provided to the Chair of the Public Administration Select Committee who is conducting an inquiry into crime statistics. They are interested in the accuracy of police recorded crime and whether they can have confidence in the crime statistics resulting from this data. More information on the inquiry, including the written and oral evidence received so far, is at 
[normal]www.parliament.uk/pasc
[normal], under “crime statistics”. In order to inform the inquiry, each Police &amp; Crime Commissioner has been asked to respond to the following questions: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1. 
[normal]              
[normal]What, if any, targets do you set for your police force? What impact do you think this has on police recording crime practices? 
[normal]2. 
[normal]              
[normal]How do you assure yourself that the recorded crime figures for your area are correct? To what extent can you trust the crime statistics for your area? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As Police &amp; Crime Commissioner for Cleveland, I scrutinise performance against the priorities for the public of my area. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Each December, Cleveland Police develops operational plans for the next year of the Police
[normal] 
[normal]&amp; Crime Plan, which set out priority areas to support the Police and Crime Commissioner's
[normal] 
[normal]objectives. The way the Force’s Operational Policing Priorities link to the Commissioner’s
[normal] 
[normal]key objectives are shown in the table below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
