[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In developing the Police &amp; Crime Plan, the PCC takes account of public consultation, listens to partners and considers current levels of crime and disorder. It may be at times,  through circumstances beyond the Force’s control, that a target can be met very quickly. For example, in 2013-14, a three year target to surpass a baseline of funds received from the Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) was set, based on trend analysis in this area. This target was achieved within three months due to numerous positive outcomes from high level cases. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Targets, where there is a victim of crime, can at times be driven not only by current crime levels, but to provide opportunities where the police can improve a support service. These targets do stimulate crime reporting but can also improve the positive outcome rate. In 2013-14, Cleveland Police are targeting the reporting of serious sexual offences, domestic abuse and hate crime. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Police performance data is made available to the Office of the PCC for a large number of strategic policing and organisational areas. The PCC attends the Strategic Performance Group (SPG), chaired by the Deputy Chief Constable and attended by senior Police Officers and the Crime Registrar. Monthly content includes: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Year-to-date analysis of operational policing priorities, 
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Crime performance 
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Antisocial behaviour data, 
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Public confidence and victim satisfaction levels, 
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Arrest/custody performance, and 
[normal]
[normal]
[normal]Crime registrar compliance. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The latter particularly focuses on the accuracy of National Crime Recording System (NCRS) information, with ‘voided crime’, ‘no crime’, ‘crimes failing the 72 hour rule’ and ‘conversion of incidents to crime’ all monitored with performance within set tolerances reported and assessed. The Crime Registrar also undertakes monthly thematic audits of the National Standard for Incident Recording (NSIR) counting rules, reporting all findings to the SPG. Any resulting corrective action is embedded in Control Room processes to ensure compliance and resilience. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In December 2013, Cleveland was subject to an HMIC crime data integrity ‘fact finding’ visit which fulfils stage 1 of a national crime data integrity inspection. Independent inspectors from HMIC, working on behalf of the Home Office, assessed the integrity of policing processes and practices and the management, reporting, recording and investigation of crime. Initial feedback indicates that Cleveland has robust and appropriate systems for ensuring integrity and transparency in crime management. A full inspection is due next year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PCC Performance Scrutiny 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Office of the PCC also conducts its own scrutiny of crime performance via a dedicated Performance Team, who assesses all data provided by the Force. They liaise with the 
[normal]Force Executive and their Performance Team on a regular basis to ensure I am briefed of any particular performance issues or evolving trends. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As PCC, I meet with the Chief Constable on a weekly basis to consider current and future issues, including performance management, via a structured agenda.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On a quarterly basis, I conduct Performance Scrutiny Meetings, where the Deputy Chief Constable answers posed questions on quarterly performance issues. Performance Exception Reports are presented, where the Force’s priorities are examined to assess if annual targets are and will be met, with any good performance highlighted and areas for improvement challenged. Since September 2013, I have been publishing these Exception Reports monthly on my website, to further inform the public and provide an extra layer of transparency in local crime performance. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The PCC, Home Office and more importantly, the public, must have complete faith that crime figures and data reported by the police is as accurate as possible and genuinely reflects the climate of crime today. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I can conclude that through my regular involvement in both the monitoring and challenging of the crime figures, I have confidence in the accuracy and integrity of the Cleveland Police crime recording processes and that information is reported, processed, managed, and challenged appropriately. This is further satisfied by the integrity and transparency in crime management being highlighted by HMIC in their recent fact finding visit.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]January 2014
